Figure 13.25 Incorporation of dummy device to mitigate charge injection and clock feedthrough.

How can we ensure that the charge injected by $M_{1}, \Delta q_{1}$, equals that absorbed by $M_{2}, \Delta q_{2}$? Assume half of $M_{1}$'s channel charge is injected onto $C_{H}$, i.e.,

$$
\begin{equation*}
\Delta q_{1}=\frac{W_{1} L_{1} C_{o x}}{2}\left(V_{C K}-V_{i n}-V_{T H 1}\right) \tag{13.36}
\end{equation*}
$$

Given $\Delta q_{2}=W_{2} L_{2} C_{o x}\left(V_{C K}-V_{i n}-V_{T H 2}\right)$, if we select $W_{2}=0.5 W_{1}$ and $L_{2}=L_{1}$, then $\Delta q_{2}=\Delta q_{1}$. However, the assumption of equal charge distribution between source and drain is generally inaccurate, making this method less appealing.

Interestingly, with the selection $W_{2}=0.5 W_{1}$ and $L_{2}=L_{1}$, the impact of clock feedthrough is diminished. As illustrated in Fig. 13.26, the total charge in $V_{\text {out }}$ is zero because

$$
\begin{equation*}
-V_{C K} \frac{W_{1} C_{o v}}{W_{1} C_{o v}+C_{H}+2 W_{2} C_{o v}}+V_{C K} \frac{2 W_{2} C_{o v}}{W_{1} C_{o v}+C_{H}+2 W_{2} C_{o v}}=0 \tag{13.37}
\end{equation*}
$$

