extrainfo:The circuit in Figure 13.26 is designed to suppress clock feedthrough using a dummy switch configuration. It utilizes NMOS transistors M1 and M2, along with capacitors, to achieve charge cancellation. The effect of clock feedthrough is minimized by balancing the charge injection from the transistors. The right side of the diagram shows the equivalent circuit with capacitors W1Cov and 2W2Cov, further aiding in charge cancellation.

Figure 13.26 Suppression of clock feedthrough using a dummy switch.
Another method to reduce charge injection involves using both PMOS and NMOS devices so that the opposing charge packets injected by each cancel each other out (Fig. 13.27). For $\Delta q_{1}$ to cancel $\Delta q_{2}$, we must have $W_{1} L_{1} C_{o x}\left(V_{C K}-V_{i n}-V_{T H N}\right)=W_{2} L_{2} C_{o x}\left(V_{i n}-\left|V_{T H P}\right|\right)$. Thus, cancellation occurs only at a single input level. Even for clock feedthrough, the circuit does not achieve complete cancellation due to the unequal gate-drain overlap capacitance of NFETs and PFETs.
