Figure 13.27 Utilization of complementary switches to mitigate charge injection.

Our understanding of the benefits of differential circuits suggests that the issue of charge injection can be alleviated through differential operation. As shown in Fig. 13.28, we hypothesize that charge injection manifests as a common-mode disturbance. However, writing $\Delta q_{1}=W L C_{o x}\left(V_{C K}-V_{i n 1}-V_{T H 1}\right)$ and $\Delta q_{2}=$ $W L C_{o x}\left(V_{C K}-V_{i n 2}-V_{T H 2}\right)$, we realize that $\Delta q_{1}=\Delta q_{2}$ only if $V_{i n 1}=V_{i n 2}$. In other words, the overall error is not suppressed for differential signals. Nevertheless, this technique both eliminates the

